data.text:
Depending on which account you believe, she was a religious fanatic, a schemer, a sexpot, a poseur, a politician, a pawn or a witch — or all of the above. Since Anne Boleyn’s execution in 1536, the conduct and implications of her life and three-year marriage to King Henry VIII have been vigorously contested, and those arguments are still alive among historians today. For good reason: her story is at the heart of England’s story.

It was Henry’s desire to marry Boleyn that led to his divorce from Catherine of Aragon, the fall of Cardinal Wolsey, the schism with the Roman Catholic church and centuries of blood-letting. But how much was Anne complicit in his decision? Did she thrust herself into the king’s eye, or
